A Book of Mine presents my entire genome in base pairs. The DNA was sampled and sequenced in December 2018, and the reads were mapped to the Human chromosome reference sequence UCSC hs38. The bases covered by my sequencing are annotated in uppercases (ACGT), and those uncovered in lowercases (acgt). 

《关于我的书》以碱基对的形式呈现我的整个基因组。 我于2018年12月进行了采样和测序，并将读数定位于人类染色体参考序列UCSC hs38。 
测序得到的、被定位的、我个体的碱基以大写字母（ACGT）注释，而没被定位的参考碱基则已以小写字母（acgt）注释。

Are these data, code, protein, or prophecy? 
它们是数据，代码，蛋白质还是预言？

Who owns it? Who made it?
谁拥有它？
谁创造了它？






I tried 23&Me when it was given to me as a birthday gift. Later, I started getting emails from the company about my potential relatives, ethnicity changes, diseases, habits that it was able to identify from my DNA through the years. 

I felt being peeked at and loss of control. 

I started to read about DNA copyright. 

On June 13, 2013, in the case of the Association for Molecular Pathology v. Myriad Genetics, Inc., the Supreme Court of the United States ruled that human genes cannot be patented in the U.S. because DNA is a "product of nature." However, the methods to read out or assemble certain sequences are still patentable, as well as sequences that are "manipulated" or man-made.






What if I made any gene of which the unique sequence is under a patent?

If any "product of nature" shall be available and accessible, are we all subject to be read by anyone?

I decided to sequence and publish my entire genome online.




How I got these DNA sequence: 


DNA was sampled by buccal swab with a sterile cotton tip applicator and stored on dry ice/-80 until prepped using the Qiagen DNeasy Blood and Tissue kit. A sequencing library was prepped using the Nextera DNA library prep kit and cleaned up using house-made AMPure-equivalent Serapure beads to a final average library size of ~350bp as indicated by gel. DNA was sequenced on the Illumina NextSeq 500 platform using a Mid-output 150 cycle kit with 2x84bp paired end reads, generating 130,139,348 reads passing filter. Reads were mapped to the UCSC hs38 X chromosome sequence using BowTie2, and variants were called using SAMtools/BCFtools. Bedtools was used to generate a coverage mask, and a custom python script then combined the reference chromosome, the coverage mask, and the variant file to generate the final text. Covered bases, defined as a very liberal 1x coverage depth (i.e. a single read) were annotated as black, and uncovered bases as grey. Variants with a quality <20 were not included. Heterozygous sites are shown in format [N…N/N…N]. Data was outputted as a .html file in 10megabase chunks, with per-base (or per-variant, in the case of variants) inline styling block specifying the text color, and converted to PDF format for printing using the wkhtmltopdf tool.


Collaborator: Ross McBee, Columbia University Department of Systems Biology
